<TEXT>
judge stanley sporkin leans way back in his 
swivel chair pops another chunk of ice from a paper cup into his 
mouth stares at the ceiling 
he is presiding over a hearing into a dicey enormously costly 
matter but you couldnt tell it by his demeanor 
he stretches he yawns he slumps he wears his halfframe 
glasses on his forehead he chews ice 
at his side millionaire charles h keating jr is the witness 
laying out his claim that clumsy overzealous regulators foolishly 
seized his lincoln savings and loan association an act likely to 
cost taxpayers 25 billion left alone it would have prospered 
keating says 
moreover according to keating the larger sampl crisis is of the 
governments own making he claims regulators took control of sampls 
that could have survived ruined the business and needlessly put a 
multibilliondollar load on taxpayers backs 
the estimated cost of the bailout has just been raised to 325 
billion including interest payments for 40 years there goes the 
peace dividend some say 
sporkin a us district court judge has to decide whether to 
let keatings claim come to trial 
keating tall trim squareshouldered wearing rimless glasses 
looks like a sunday school superintendent 
he is famous for three tactics filing suits spending what is 
necessary to get what he wants and hiring his antagonists often 
at big salaries 
his very name raises goosebumps on political skin five senators 
are hurting because they accepted 13 million in campaign 
contributions from keating then met with him to hear his 
complaints about heavyhanded federal regulators 
keating didnt help them when taking note of the rumors that 
his money influenced several political figures to take up my 
cause he said i certainly hope so 
whatever aid he got from the senators it was not enough to 
prevent the takeover of his sampl empire based in california 
the regulators declared keatings highflying tactics made 
lincoln unsafe and unsound and put its depositors at risk their 
money dissipated in junk bond gambles they said he used a complex 
tax scheme to funnel lincolns deposits into his arizona real 
estate ventures 
his testimony is peppered with aggressive words 
preposterous reckless vendetta he says the 
examination of his books by the federal home loan bank board was 
vicious even savage 
he says he ran a nontraditional sampl he says the government 
was out to destroy him he says the us league of savings 
institutions resentful of the competition lobbied against him 
on the stand thursday to prove evil motivation he cited a memo 
from one regulator 
even our lawyers are finally getting the message it said 
under every document is another scam and they seem to finally 
understand what type of thieves we are dealing with and why we need 
to get them out 
keating brought out that the author of the memo kevin 
oconnell is the son of the william b oconnell who was 
president of the league at the time kevin oconnell a witness for 
the government was seated at the government table 
sporkin acted like a man who could not believe his ears he 
chuckled he pointed to the younger oconnell 
it was this gentlemans father who was president of the us 
league he asked unbelievingly 
oconnell said nothing later he told reporters the memo was 
selfexplanatory 
if sporkin rules in keatings favor the entire sampl bailout 
could be thrown into question it would lend credence to keatings 
view that sampl takeovers created a glutted real estate market 
jeopardizing additional sampls which saw the value of their 
mortgages fall 
the government asked sporkin to quash keatings suit a motion 
which could be routinely disposed of sporkin set aside two days 
for a hearing then he set aside six more days now the hearing 
had run through its 23rd day 
between these two keating and sporkin has developed a rapport 
courtroom spectators say sporkin understands finances an 
accountant before he was a lawyer he was chief of enforcement at 
the securities and exchange commission and chief counsel to the cia 
before he became a judge 
keating is solicitous to him before the house banking 
committee keating exercised his fifth amendment rights to remain 
silent but is eager to make his case in sporkins court 
every so often up pops james murphy the lawyer hired to 
represent the office of thrift supervision successor agency to the 
home loan bank board 
he argues that keating keeps veering into areas that have no 
relevance this is a hearing on a motion not a trial 
sporkin waves him off im just listening and i believe i have 
a responsibility to listen he tells murphy plus he says 
grinning its a lot more interesting than a lot of things i have 
to listen to 
