the government will sponsor a threeyear 29 
million research project aimed at reducing or preventing physical 
frailty in the elderly two federal agencies announced sunday 
the national institute on aging and the national center for 
nursing research said sites in eight states will be used for the 
ficsit project short for frailty and injuries cooperative 
studies of intervention techniques 
more than 1500 volunteers will participate in the program to 
include exercise ranging from the oriental practice of tai chi to 
aerobic dance education to make older people aware of accident 
risks and rehabilitation to improve physical conditioning 
millions of older people are frail lacking strength mobility 
balance and endurance which can make them susceptible to serious 
falls nursing home admissions and a loss of independence 
according to the nia 
the new trials highlight the fact that frailty and injuries 
are not the inevitable outcome of aging said nia director dr t 
franklin williams instead they are problems for which we have 
now found some very viable solutions 
among people over age 75 more than 32 percent are unable to 
climb stairs 40 percent are unable to walk two blocks 7 percent 
cannot walk across a small room and 22 percent cannot lift 10 
pounds the nia said fortytwo percent of nursing home residents 
cannot get out of a chair without help 
