<TEXT>
people power scaled the majestic 
himalayas last week and a king bowed to a street revolution 
promising multiparty democracy 
a political stalemate is holding up the reform however and 
some fear nepals movement toward freedom will be turned back 
early monday negotiations between opposition and government 
leaders collapsed and hundreds of angry protesters camped out 
around the site of the talks refusing to let the politicians leave 
on april 8 two days after the bloodiest crackdown in nepals 
modern history 44yearold king birendra gave in to the popular 
revolt declared the press to be free and released political 
prisoners 
tens of thousands of nepalis their faces painted red in 
celebration danced through the streets of the capital shouting 
victory victory 
their tears of joy dried quickly the 17 million people in this 
landlocked nation of breathtaking beauty face serious questions 
how can they establish true democracy in a country where the 
king is allpowerful and viewed by many as a living god what means 
should they use 
the questions are not new 
three decades ago nepal experimented with multiparty politics 
for 18 months the experiment ended abruptly when birendras 
father king mahendra dismissed the government and banned 
political parties which he accused of corruption and incompetence 
now the nepali congress party which mahendra banned has 
returned to haunt his son joining with a leftist coalition the 
party led the movement for democracy that drew hundreds of 
thousands of people into the streets 
doctors pilots government workers students and intellectuals 
conducted strikes the movement peaked april 6 and the goverment 
cracked down up to 200 people were killed when police opened fire 
in katmandu and elsewhere 
two days later a special television broadcast told the story 
the king was establishing a multiparty system in exchange the 
opposition announced an end to its agitation 
new battle lines have been drawn since then 
after the television announcement birendra invited the 
opposition to join an interim government that would prepare for 
elections foreign minister pashupati rana said the kings role 
would be diminished 
opposition parties balked and have threatened to return to the 
streets unless the king dissolves the partyless national assemby 
or rashtriya panchayat and scraps the constitution 
under the system established by his father birendra dominates 
the government he appoints onefifth of the national assembly and 
has a say in the nomination of candidates for the other elected 
seats 
the constitution gives him control of the executive legislative 
and judicial branches of government 
observers say the oppositions first job will be among the most 
difficult to nullify or at least limit the kings power 
we have scored a victory no doubt but we have not staged a 
french revolution said dilli raj regmi cofounder of the nepali 
congress party the scenario has not totally changed and we still 
have limited rights 
he described the monarchy as useless 
the opposition held all the trump cards and should have 
demanded dissolution of the panchayat and the abolition of the 
constitution from the beginning said lok raj baral a professor 
of political science at tribhuvan university the only one in nepal 
unless the opposition acts quickly baral said the result will 
be the same old game of palace intrigue a reference to 
birendras past record of playing one political group against 
another 
krishna prasad bhattarai president of the nepali congress 
party said we have to go stepbystep the agitation was 
stopped to avoid further bloodshed and because we are a 
responsible party he said 
bhattarai added however that if he does not meet our 
demands the king will lose his crown 
he said birendras concession is only the first step toward 
wider democracy that can be achieved only after general elections 
there are no indications when elections will be held 
we are willing to wait one month one year or three years or 
ad infinitum bhattarai said 
others might not share his patience 
nepal with a per capita gross national product of about 160 a 
year is one of worlds poorest countries and 75 percent of the 
people are illiterate 
during the crackdown april 6 tens of thousands of angry men 
threw rocks and sticks at police set fire to government buildings 
and smashed windows throughout the capital 
baral said the people now are ready to assert their rights 
because they have tasted the power of mass movement once the 
peoples movement has started no army or police can stop them 
</TEXT>
