<TEXT>
the valdez principles 10 rules for 
corporate conduct regarding the environment have become a focal 
point of the shareholder activist movement this year 
they were composed by the coalition for environmentally 
responsible economies a consortium of environmental organizations 
and social investors that include the sierra club national audobon 
society national wildlife federation and the controllers of new 
york city new york state and california who manage large pension 
funds that invest in stocks of many companies 
although the principles are named after the exxon oil spill that 
fouled valdez alaska in march 1989 the ceres group says it began 
formulating them well before then they were released last 
september 
so far no company has pledged to become a signatory to the 
principles but many have expressed interest and some have promised 
to provide progress reports on how they plan to adhere to them the 
ceres group intends to release a corporate guide for how to become 
a signatory later this month 
here are the principles as provided by ceres 
1 protection of the biosphere minimize and seek to eliminate 
the release of pollutants that cause damage to the air water or 
earth or its inhabitants safeguard habitats in rivers lakes 
wetlands coastal zones and oceans and minimize contributing to the 
greenhouse effect depletion of the ozone layer acid rain or smog 
2 sustainable use of natural resources make sustainable use of 
renewable resources such as water soils and forests conserve 
nonrenewable natural resources through efficient use and careful 
planning protect wildlife habitat open spaces and wilderness 
while preserving biodiversity 
3 reduction and disposal of wastes minimize the creation of 
waste especially hazardous waste and wherever possible recycle 
materials dispose of waste through safe and responsible methods 
4 wise use of energy make every effort to use environmentally 
safe and sustainable energy sources to meet our needs invest in 
improved energy efficiency and conservation in our operations 
maximize energy efficiency of products we produce or sell 
5 risk reduction minimize environmental health and safety 
risks to employees and communities in which we operate by employing 
safe technologies and operating procedures and by being constantly 
prepared for emergencies 
6 marketing of safe products and services sell products or 
services that minimize environmental impacts and are safe as 
consumers use them inform consumers of environmental impacts of 
products or services 
7 damage compensation take responsibility for harm we cause to 
the environment by making every effort to fully restore the 
environment and to compensate persons adversely affected 
8 disclosure disclose to employees and to the public incidents 
relating to operations that cause environmental harm or pose health 
and safety hazards disclose potential environmental health or 
safety hazards posed by operations and take no action against 
employees who report conditions that create a danger to the 
environment or pose health and safety hazards 
9 environmental directors and managers have a person qualified 
to represent environmental interests on the board commit 
management resources to implement these principles including 
funding an office of vice president for environmental affairs or an 
equivalent executive position reporting directly to the ceo to 
monitor and report upon implementation efforts 
10 assessment and annual audit conduct and make public an 
annual selfevaluation of progress in implementing these principles 
and in complying with all applicable laws and regulations 
throughout worldwide operations work toward timely creation of 
independent environmental audit procedures completed annually and 
made available to the public 
</TEXT>
