<DOCNO> AP900415-0076 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a senior official said sudan does not 
intend to accept the economic reform program proposed by the 
international monetary fund which includes a sharp devaluation of 
the countrys currency 
col salah eldin karrar a member of the ruling 15man military 
council was quoted by alsudan alhadith newspaper as saying the 
government will accept only its own economic reform program 
we will not back out on our economic program whether there is 
agreement or disagreement with the imf he said 
the imf declared sudan ineligible for loans in 1986 the 
military government which came to power june 30 has held two 
inconclusive rounds of talks with the international agency the 
next round of talks start may 5 
karrar gave no details of the governments program except to say 
it was a counterproposal to an imf proposal he said a recent imf 
proposal to devalue the sudanese pound was unacceptable 
the imf proposed that the official exchange rate be devalued to 
15 pounds to the dollar from 45 pounds currently and the tourist 
rate be changed to 30 pounds to the dollar from 1210 pounds 
karrar said 
the sudanese government is burdened by a 13 billion foreign 
debt the 7yearold civil war in the south costs the government 1 
million a day 
</TEXT>
